Case File: Sublevel 3 Broadcast Incident

The sublevel looked like other retail spaces I had seen before. The aisles were wide, the flooring shiny, and fluorescent lights hung in long, buzzing rows. The shelving units stood tall and straight, but they were completely empty. There wasn't any packaging, no labels, and no price tags. It was just bare metal and smooth surfaces, repeating endlessly as the aisles branched off and came back together. I had been wandering through this space for some time when I first noticed the sound.

Initially, I thought it was another strange noise. A faint clicking, irregular and almost rhythmic. It didn’t echo like footsteps do. It felt localized and solid. Following the sound led me to a service corridor that shouldn’t have been there, hidden between two shelving units that were supposed to be continuous. At the end of the corridor was a small office. Inside, to my surprise, sat a computer. It was old, with a beige case and physical buttons. The monitor was thick enough to seem outdated, even by earlier standards. There were no cables connecting it to the walls, yet it was on. The screen showed a blank desktop, with no wallpaper or icons, except for a single audio control panel that was already open.

That should not have been possible.

I approached it carefully. The air in the room felt heavier—not warmer or colder, just denser, as if the pressure had increased slightly. The fluorescent lights outside the office appeared dimmer from within, their hum fading into something dull and far away. The computer responded right away when I touched it. There was no boot-up sequence, no delay. The audio panel reacted as if it had been waiting for me. That was when I realized the system connected to the store’s announcement speakers. I hadn’t seen them before, but once I did, they were hard to miss. They were mounted high on the walls between the aisles, identical and silent.

I don’t know why I decided to record a message. There was no plan and no intention to communicate. The thought didn’t feel like a decision. It came already formed and justified, like something I had to do before moving on.

I pressed the button. The microphone crackled softly. The sound echoed faintly through the office speakers and then spread out into the store. The delay felt wrong, too slow, as if the space had to think before allowing the sound to exist. I tried to speak. No words came out. Not because I couldn’t talk, but the moment I tried, something shifted. I felt pressure behind my eyes and in my chest, as if I were being pulled forward from within. Not physically, but internally, as if whatever makes me who I am was stretching toward the microphone. When sound finally came through, I realised it wasn’t following my mouth. The voice over the speakers was mine; it was trying to speak what I was thinking, but it lagged behind my thoughts, turning into an almost demonic screech followed by a strange lullaby.

