Case File: The Blinding Light Incident

I did not walk into the next sublevel. There was no corridor, no doorway, and no gradual shift in layout. One moment, I stood between two empty walls, Then everything turned to light. Not brightness. Not illumination. Light in a way that replaced everything else.

It came without direction or source. There was no flash or warning glare. The space itself seemed to flip, as if darkness had been violently removed. For a brief time I cannot measure, I was engulfed by pure white intensity, uniform and absolute. It felt like my skin was melting. Not burning, not tearing. Dissolving. As if the boundary between my body and the environment no longer existed. I felt an overwhelming sensation that my surface was turning fluid, that my outline was vanishing, that whatever separated me from the outside was being smoothed away layer by layer. There was no pain in the usual way. Pain involves nerves, signals, and sequences. This feeling was more immediate. It was like being told, all at once, that my physical form was negotiable.

I tried to close my eyes. It didn’t help. The light wasn’t entering my sight. It was my sight.

Then the visions began.

<br>
[[File:Thelightcase.png|center|link=|500px]]
<br>

They did not come one after another; they overlapped. Shapes unfolded into other shapes without transitioning. Impossible geometries rotated through each other, not in three dimensions, but in something close to that. Angles bent inward. Lines crossed where space should not allow them to. Structures built themselves while also collapsing, repeating the process endlessly without contradiction. I saw corridors made of triangles that folded into spheres. Staircases that climbed across flat planes and somehow ended up beneath themselves. Rooms with all corners, no walls, no floors, yet fully closed in.

Patterns repeated at scales that made no sense. A shape the size of a building would suddenly appear as a detail within itself. The same structure nested endlessly, recursion without depth. I could not tell if I was moving through these forms or if they were moving through me. Some of the geometry noticed me. Not in a conscious way. More like a function adjusting for an unexpected variable. Lines realigned. Shapes hesitated. One configuration collapsed too soon, as if my presence had disrupted an equation that never intended to include a human observer. That was when the terror truly began.

Not because of what I was seeing, but because I was certain this was not meant to be perceived from the inside. These visions were not environments; they were internal mechanisms briefly exposed. Like seeing the inside of something that was only meant to be experienced from the outside. The light intensified again. For a moment, I believed I was gone. Not dying. Gone. Converted into something else or spread too thin to reassemble.

Then it stopped. It only took one blink before I was on the floor of a new sublevel.

