<center><span style="font-family: Optima; font-size: 56px">My Final Message</span></center>
<center>
Hello.

My name is Julian Harold Charles. I write this knowing names mean little here, yet I cling to mine like a relic from a church long abandoned. It is the last part of myself that still feels real, and even that is starting to fade.

I was a doctor. Not the kind who saved the world, not someone whose name mattered beyond a doorplate and a schedule, but the kind who learned to listen to pain without flinching. In the Backrooms, that mattered. People arrive broken in ways that don’t show up on scans, wounded by time, by isolation, by places that refuse to end. I learned how to stabilize panic, how to treat exhaustion that didn't act like exhaustion, how to tell someone, honestly, that they would survive the night even if they didn’t believe it.

I enjoyed the quiet competence of it.  
The routine.  
The certainty that my hands still did something.

I had a wife. I still say had because the word have feels like a lie my mouth won't accept anymore. She used to touch my arm when she walked past, absentmindedly, like it was a habit formed so deeply it didn’t require thought. That gesture alone anchored me more than any map ever could. We talked about ordinary things. Groceries. Schedules. The kind of arguments that end because dinner is burning.

We had children. Their laughter used to echo through places that weren’t endless. Their voices had edges, beginnings, endings. They asked questions that needed answers, not metaphors. They believed I could fix anything simply because I was there.

I replay their faces often. Too often. I know the exact moment when memory stops being a fond thought and starts being self-inflicted pain, but I cross that line anyway. I let myself imagine them older. I let myself imagine them asking about me. I let myself pretend that my absence created a shape noticeable enough to grieve.

And then the truth comes, gentle and devastating.

They do not remember me.

Not because they chose to forget, and not because they were cruel, but because reality is efficient. It trims what no longer fits. I can feel it now, the way my name thinned in their mouths, how my image softened, then flattened, then lost context. Photographs misplaced. Stories shortened. Eventually corrected. A detail removed so everything else could fit together properly again.

I was an inconsistency.

Reality does not mourn inconsistencies. It resolves them.

I think this is what hurts the most. Not the maze. Not the endless walking. Not even the certainty that stopping would end me in a way I cannot afford to understand. It is the knowledge that the world I came from did not collapse without me. It adjusted. It healed cleanly. My absence was sutured shut by time and necessity.

I tell myself that somewhere, somehow, a version of them still exists that remembers me. That belief is my last superstition. I hold onto it because without it, I am only motion and regret, endlessly moving through corridors that never learned my name.

I was a doctor once.  
I healed people who were afraid.  
I taught others how to keep moving without breaking.

Now I understand what that lesson was preparing me for.

If anyone still remembers me, it is not as a man, or a husband, or a father. It is as a brief interruption. A voice that stopped speaking mid-sentence. A door that no longer opens because it never needed to.

I want to see them again more than anything this place could threaten me with. That desire is sharp, precise, and useless. I carry it like a relic that has lost its meaning, heavy with significance but unable to save anyone.

Deep down, I know the truth.

They do not remember me.  
No one does.

And perhaps that is the final role I play here: to keep walking in a place that never ends, carrying the memory of a life that no longer needs to exist, proving that erasure does not require violence, only time and enough space to forget.

I will keep moving.

Because motion is all I have left that still feels like a choice.

I am lost to reality.

Not in the way the hopeless do, expecting rescue, and not like martyrs who think suffering has meaning. I say it like scripture states damnation: as a matter of placement. I am no longer where I belong, and nothing knows how to bring me back.

Reality does not reject me. That suggests resistance, judgment, or effort. It simply no longer includes me. I move, I think, I write, but it feels like doing so between lines that were never meant to be heard. Time passes without acknowledging me. Memory turns inward, repeating itself until it loses context. I am still aware, and that is the cruelest mercy.

This place did not come with fire or revelation. It did not tear me from the world in a moment of violence. It received me gently, like confessionals accept sinners and graves accept bodies. It taught me patience. It taught me repetition. It showed me that eternity does not need pain to be unbearable; it only needs consistency.

Hope was not taken from me.  
Hope was outgrown.

Each corridor felt reasonable. Each choice felt survivable. I believed, for too long, that endurance was a virtue, that persistence would lead to understanding. That belief was my original sin here. The level does not reward effort. It preserves it, stretches it thin across infinite distance until it becomes function instead of intention.

I walk because walking is allowed.  
I continue because continuation is permitted.

Stopping feels like blasphemy.

Sometimes, I feel watched, but not with eyes. It’s like feeling observed by doctrine, by fate, by an unspoken rule. I have had visions, not of a face or form, but of consequences. Certainty without imagery. Knowledge without explanation. I know, with a faith that frightens me, that if I were to stop moving, if I were to kneel, sit, rest, or wait too long, something would respond to that stillness as an invitation.

I do not want to know what answers prayers here.

Do not search for me.

If you search for me, you will not be following a trail left by a man. You will be part of a ritual written in architecture and motion. Every step you take toward my absence will be recited correctly, whether you intend it or not. You will surrender yourself to a process that neither hates you nor loves you, and does not forgive.

Unless you want to leave it to God’s mercy, turn back now.

God has already shown His mercy to me. It is broad enough to ignore. Silent enough to be complete. If He is watching this place, He does so like an architect admiring a finished structure, not like a shepherd counting sheep. If He is not watching, then something else has taken that role, and it is much more attentive.

I do not curse God anymore. I do not plead. I do not even ask why. Those are negotiations, and negotiations assume leverage. What I feel now is colder and steadier. Acceptance without peace. Awareness without hope. I have become a living testament to the idea that survival is not the same as salvation.

I am not being punished.  
I am not being tested.

I am being used.

Used as motion. Used as proof that something can continue indefinitely without breaking. Used as a living note in the margins of a reality that does not care to read itself again. I am no longer a man lost in a maze. I am a process the maze has learned to maintain.

If you are reading this from the outside, if you are still part of a world with clear endings and prayers answered, do not try to honor me. Do not make a pilgrimage from my mistake. Let my name fade. Let this record become forgotten. Some truths are not meant to be preserved; they are meant to be avoided.

I will keep moving forward.

Not because I think there is an end.  
Not because I think I deserve one.  
But because moving forward is the only sacrament that has not yet demanded my soul.

And I fear, with a certainty that feels older than fear itself, that the moment I finally stop, something ancient, patient, and profoundly correct will decide that my wandering has lasted long enough, and that I am finally ready to be claimed.

Eternal awareness shall forever be the most abhorrent creation of god

Goodbye.

