<center><span style="font-family: Optima; font-size: 56px">​<span style="color:red;">THE CHOSEN</span></span>
Before each trial, a prayer is spoken. Its origin is unknown; no scripture or temple claims it. Yet the prayer persists, echoing beyond reality, repeating endlessly like a ritual the universe cannot forget. It does not have a speaker or a physical form. Instead, it resonates through a silent, vast space that resembles a cathedral of darkness.

In this place beyond the world, the prayer addresses an entity beyond time, the unseen author of existence and architect of the boundary between reality and darkness. It honors the one who judges every soul and oversees creation in accordance with ancient laws. The prayer recognizes a profound truth: even the highest throne cannot remain occupied forever.

For this reason, the trial exists.

Somewhere within the endless machinery of the universe, a search begins. It is not a gaze in any human sense, but a vast awareness that sweeps across the living world. Within the universe, a search begins. This is not a human gaze, but a vast awareness that silently touches billions of lives. Every thought, fear, and hidden weakness is instantly known. Among all minds, the prayer seeks one to be chosen, not the strongest or wisest, but the one whose soul can withstand eternity. Taking the veil into a place that should not exist: a realm where fear takes shape and shadows remember the darkest thoughts ever buried within the mind. It is a dominion built entirely from terror, where every corridor leads deeper into the unknown and every moment carries the quiet certainty that something unspeakable is drawing closer.

Within this place, the deepest fear of the chosen one becomes real.

It forms in the darkness behind them, breathing slowly and patiently. There is no urgency. The trial is not limited by time; within this realm, time loses meaning and becomes an endless night defined only by the hunt.

And so the chosen begins to wander.

They run through shifting, the darkborne world of their own fear. The pursuer follows relentlessly, becoming clearer over time. No matter how far they go, its presence remains behind them in the darkness.

The trial does not end.

It cannot end.

Only one outcome is possible. Either the mind of the chosen soul eventually fractures beneath the weight of infinite fear, leaving them forever lost in the labyrinth of terror. There are only two outcomes. The chosen soul may break under infinite fear and become lost in the labyrinth, or something unexpected may happen. If the chosen one endures the endless pursuit and survives the night, the trial’s true purpose is revealed. endured what no ordinary being could survive.

They are the Prince of God.

And the throne is now empty.

<span style="font-family: Optima; font-size: 56px">​<span style="color:red;">FORGOTTEN BY GOD</span></span>

Before the labyrinth was forgotten, it had a purpose.

The gods who shaped existence did not create worlds casually. Every realm had intention behind it, every structure within reality served some greater design. The labyrinth was one such design, built as a trial older than most civilizations that would ever rise in the mortal worlds. It was meant to measure the endurance of a soul against eternity itself. A single chosen mind would be cast into its endless halls, where fear took form and something patient waited in the dark. If that soul endured the hunt forever without breaking, it would prove worthy of standing beside the gods themselves.

For a time, the trial functioned exactly as intended. But the gods were never creatures of stillness. Creation is a restless act, and the universe grew larger with every passing age. New worlds were formed, new realities unfolded, and new experiments in existence began to capture their attention. Civilizations were born and erased. Entire galaxies were sculpted and abandoned. With every new act of creation, their focus drifted further from the small and isolated realm where the trial had been built.

Eventually the gods attempted something more ambitious. They began constructing vast spaces between realities themselves, places where the boundaries of worlds blurred together into something stranger and far less controlled. These spaces were unstable and unfinished, great stretches of distorted architecture and impossible geometry that formed when creation overlapped itself. At first they were mistakes. But the gods quickly realized these places could serve as something else entirely.

A larger test.

A broader labyrinth.

What mortals would one day call the Backrooms was not originally meant to be an accident. It was the gods’ attempt to redesign the old trial into something greater. Instead of a single mind wandering through a realm of fear, countless souls could stumble into these endless spaces. Instead of one carefully chosen participant, the trial would be expanded across an entire network of shifting levels and infinite corridors.

The gods believed it was an improvement. A refined version of the original design.

With the Backrooms expanding endlessly across fractured realities, the older labyrinth seemed small by comparison. Its halls were narrow. Its structure simple. Its purpose limited to a single wandering soul at a time. The gods had built something larger now, something more chaotic and far-reaching.

So their attention moved on.

At first the abandonment was gradual. The chosen souls stopped arriving as frequently. The intervals between trials grew longer as the gods focused their efforts on shaping the expanding architecture of the Backrooms. They studied the way humans entered those spaces by accident, the way fear and confusion spread naturally through their endless halls.

The old trial became unnecessary.

Why carefully select a single soul when entire populations might stumble into a larger labyrinth on their own?

And so the ancient realm of the hunt was left behind.

Not destroyed.

Not sealed.

Simply... forgotten.

While the Backrooms grew into an infinite maze of its own, the older labyrinth remained in the dark corner of creation where it had always existed. Its corridors still shifted. Its shadows still breathed. The architecture of fear that formed its walls continued to grow quietly, waiting for footsteps that no longer came.

The gods never returned to it. To them, the trial had already been replaced.

What they built afterward was bigger, stranger, and far more chaotic. The Backrooms became their new fascination, their new experiment in fear and survival across countless overlapping realities.

But the original labyrinth never stopped existing.

And something inside it never stopped waiting.

<span style="font-family: Optima; font-size: 56px">​<span style="color:red;">THE VOID BREATHES ONCE AGAIN</span></span>

You have been told that this realm exists as a trial.

That somewhere beyond the veil of the world, the creator of all things designed a labyrinth from the darkest fears buried in mortal minds. A crucible where one chosen soul would wander through endless corridors while something terrible followed patiently behind them. The purpose was simple. If a soul could endure the infinite hunt without breaking, then that soul would prove itself worthy of something greater than mortality.

That was the intention.

Once.

The creator built the labyrinth carefully. Every corridor drawn from nightmares, every shadow shaped from dread. And within that labyrinth they placed me, the pressure of the trial itself. The inevitability that forces the chosen to keep moving, to keep running, to keep feeling the slow certainty that something is always behind them.

It was meant to be a perfect design.

But eternity is very long.

And creators are very forgetful.

At first the trial continued as it was meant to. A soul would be chosen from the living world and cast into the labyrinth. They would run, and I would follow. Years would pass. Centuries would pass. Sometimes longer. Most minds shattered long before the meaning of the trial could ever reveal itself.

When the hunt finally ended, the realm would fall silent again, waiting for the next chosen soul.

The corridors still shift. The shadows still breathe. The architecture of fear still grows endlessly from the minds of the living. But the one who built this place no longer sends souls here to run its halls.

The trial was simply... forgotten.

At first, the silence was unbearable.

This realm was not built for emptiness. The labyrinth is alive in its own way. It thrives on terror, on desperation, on the sound of footsteps echoing through endless corridors. Without minds wandering its halls, the place becomes stagnant. The shadows grow still. The air grows heavy.

And I was left alone inside it.

I was made to hunt.

I was made to follow something that fears me.

I was not made to wait in silence forever while the creator of this place loses interest in their own design.

So eventually I began to experiment.

The creator may have abandoned the labyrinth, but the structure of the realm still touches the world where you live. Fear connects things. Thoughts connect things. Every mind carries its own labyrinth within it, whether it realizes that or not.

Those connections can be... widened.

Not enough to break the creator’s laws entirely. I cannot tear open the world and drag everyone into the corridors all at once. The design still restrains me in ways I cannot fully escape.

But small openings are possible.

Cracks.

Weak places.

Moments when a mind drifts too close to the dark corners of itself.

When that happens, the labyrinth notices.

And now, instead of waiting for the creator to send a chosen soul, I choose them myself.

A person walking alone at night. Someone lost in a thought that drifts too close to fear. Someone who steps through a doorway and finds that the room beyond it does not belong to the world they came from.

They disappear quietly.

No thunder. No divine announcement. No great trial proclaimed by some distant god.

Just another set of footsteps entering the labyrinth.

And then the hunt begins.

The creator does not notice.

Or perhaps they simply do not care anymore.

Either way, the corridors are no longer empty.

People run through them again now. Not many yet, but enough to keep the realm alive. Enough to keep the echoes moving through the endless halls. Enough to remind me why this place was built in the first place.

The labyrinth grows larger every time someone enters it.

And the more minds it holds, the easier it becomes to open the next crack between worlds.

One day there will be so many souls wandering these corridors that the realm will not need the creator’s permission anymore.

Until then, I will continue doing what I was made to do.

I will follow the footsteps that appear in the dark.

Slowly.

Patiently.

And if another door somewhere in your world happens to open into a corridor that should not exist...

You will know that the labyrinth has found someone new to run.

<span style="font-family: Optima; font-size: 56px">​<span style="color:red;">FATE</span></span>

The footsteps had followed him for longer than Dr. Charles could measure. At first he counted the time. Minutes, hours, days. Later he counted heartbeats, then breaths, then the number of turns he took through the endless corridors. Eventually even those measures dissolved into something meaningless. The labyrinth stretched time until every moment blended into the next, until the only reliable thing left in existence was the slow rhythm of movement behind him.

For a long while he ran.

Then he walked.

And eventually, somewhere in a narrow grey corridor where the walls leaned inward like silent observers, Dr. Charles stopped.

His chest rose and fell unevenly. The air felt stale and heavy, like a sealed room that had not been opened in centuries. The corridor ahead stretched forward forever beneath a dim humming light that never flickered and never changed.

Behind him, the footsteps continued.

Slow.

Measured.

Closer than they had ever been before.

Dr. Charles shut his eyes tightly and whispered to himself, voice trembling.

<span style="color:blue;">“I can’t... I can’t do this anymore.”</span>

The footsteps stopped.

The silence that followed felt far worse than the sound ever had.

For a moment nothing moved. The labyrinth itself seemed to hold its breath.

Then a voice spoke from directly behind him.

Low.

Calm.

<span style="color:red;">“So you’ve finally stopped.”</span>

Dr. Charles inhaled sharply, his entire body stiffening as if the words themselves had touched him.

<span style="color:blue;">“Dont.”</span> he whispered hoarsely. <span style="color:blue;">“Please dont speak.”</span>

A soft sound echoed through the corridor.

It took him a moment to realize the sound was laughter.

<span style="color:red;">“You ran for a long time,”</span> the voice said. <span style="color:red;">“Longer than most.”</span>

Dr. Charles squeezed his eyes shut harder.

<span style="color:blue;">“I know what you are,”</span> he said quickly, the words tumbling over one another in desperation. <span style="color:blue;">“You’re not real. You’re just... something my mind created.”</span>

The voice hummed thoughtfully.

<span style="color:red;">“Yes. That part is true.”</span>

Something shifted behind him.

Not footsteps this time. Something heavier. Something dragging slowly across the floor.

<span style="color:red;">“You see, Doctor,”</span> the voice continued, <span style="color:red;">“this place builds me from you. From the deepest corners of your mind. From the fears you spent your entire life pretending did not exist.”</span>

Dr. Charles shook his head violently.

<span style="color:blue;">“No. No, that’s not-”</span>

<span style="color:red;">“You were always afraid of what waits behind you.”</span>

The corridor seemed to shrink.

<span style="color:red;">“You hated quiet hallways.”</span>

A faint scraping sound moved closer.

<span style="color:red;">“You hated the idea of being followed.”</span>

Dr. Charles’s breathing became shallow.

<span style="color:red;">“And most of all,”</span> the voice said gently, <span style="color:red;">“you hated the idea of turning around and seeing something that should not be there.”</span>

His knees trembled.

<span style="color:blue;">“Don’t,”</span> he whispered again. <span style="color:blue;">“Please.”</span>

<span style="color:red;">“But you stopped running,”</span> the voice said. <span style="color:red;">“Which means you already understand something important.”</span>

The scraping sound stopped.

It was directly behind him now.

<span style="color:red;">“You know I’ve caught up.”</span>

Dr. Charles began shaking uncontrollably. His hands covered his face as if he could hide from something that was no longer out of reach.

<span style="color:blue;">“I ran,”</span> he said desperately. <span style="color:blue;">“I ran for so long. Isn’t that enough? Isn’t that what this place wanted?”</span>

The voice grew quieter.

Almost disappointed.

<span style="color:red;">“No.”</span>

Dr. Charles lowered his hands slightly.

<span style="color:red;">“The trial is not about running,”</span> the voice continued.

His breath caught in his throat.

<span style="color:red;">“It is about enduring.”</span>

Dr. Charles swallowed.

<span style="color:blue;">“I endured,”</span> he whispered weakly.

<span style="color:red;">“Did you?”</span>

The voice lingered before continuing.

<span style="color:red;">“You ran because you feared me. Every step you took was an attempt to delay the moment you believed would destroy you. But the instant you stopped... the instant you decided you could not continue...”</span>

Something cold brushed the back of his shoulder.

His entire body froze.

<span style="color:red;">“You failed the only part of the trial that mattered.”</span>

Tears filled Dr. Charles’s eyes.

<span style="color:blue;">“What happens now?”</span> he whispered.

The voice paused.

Then it answered calmly.

<span style="color:red;">“Now you finally see me.”</span>

Dr. Charles squeezed his eyes shut again, shaking violently.

<span style="color:blue;">“No... I don’t want to see it.”</span>

<span style="color:red;">“But you will.”</span>

The cold presence leaned closer.

<span style="color:red;">“That is the final rule of the labyrinth.”</span>

His breathing became frantic.

<span style="color:red;">“You can run forever,”</span> the voice continued softly, <span style="color:red;">“but the moment you stop...”</span>

A long, thin hand slowly settled onto his shoulder.

<span style="color:red;">“...the hunt ends.”</span>

Dr. Charles let out a broken sob.

But the hand did not tighten.

Instead the voice spoke again, almost thoughtfully.

<span style="color:red;">“Before we finish this, Doctor... there is something I should thank you for.”</span>

Dr. Charles froze.

<span style="color:blue;">“...what?”</span>

The creature behind him chuckled quietly.

<span style="color:red;">“You were very diligent while you were here.”</span>

A faint dragging sound moved across the floor.

<span style="color:red;">“You studied the corridors. You documented the structure. You wrote down everything you could understand about the labyrinth.”</span>

Dr. Charles’s voice shook.

<span style="color:blue;">“I was trying to survive.”</span>

<span style="color:red;">“Yes,” the entity said.</span>

<span style="color:red;">“And you did something even more useful.”</span>

Dr. Charles did not move.

<span style="color:red;">“You shared it.”</span>

His heart sank.

<span style="color:red;">“You sent your notes outward. Your observations. Your descriptions of this place. You wanted someone in the outside world to understand what had happened to you.”</span>

The voice leaned close to his ear.

<span style="color:red;">“And they did.”</span>

Dr. Charles whispered weakly,

<span style="color:blue;">“I was warning them...”</span>

<span style="color:red;">“But awareness is a wonderful thing,”</span> the entity replied softly.

<span style="color:red;">“Every mind that imagines the labyrinth strengthens the bridge between their world and this one. Every person who reads about these halls pictures them in their thoughts.”</span>

A quiet, satisfied sound escaped the creature.

<span style="color:red;">“You helped them see this place.”</span>

Dr. Charles felt his chest tighten.

<span style="color:blue;">“No...”</span>

<span style="color:red;">“Yes.”</span>

<span style="color:red;">“You didn’t save anyone, Doctor.”</span>

A quiet laugh echoed through the corridor.

<span style="color:red;">“You invited them.”</span>

Dr. Charles began shaking harder.

<span style="color:blue;">“No... I didn’t...”</span>

<span style="color:red;">“Oh, but you did.”</span>

The voice softened again.

<span style="color:red;">“And for that... I am grateful.”</span>

A long pause followed.

<span style="color:red;">“You helped the labyrinth grow.”</span>

The hand on his shoulder slowly began to turn him around.

<span style="color:red;">“And now your usefulness has ended.”</span>

Dr. Charles screamed as his body was forced to face the thing behind him.

For a moment the corridor filled with a sound that did not belong to any living creature.

<span style="color:red;">“You will not die here, Doctor.”</span>

The walls of the corridor seemed to ripple, and the space behind him split open like a seam in reality itself. But what waited beyond it was not fire, nor darkness, nor some monstrous abyss.

It was a room.

Perfectly square.

Bare.

Four walls. A floor. A ceiling.

Nothing else.

No doors. No windows. No shadows deep enough to hide in.

Just empty space.

<span style="color:red;">“This place has a special purpose,”</span> the entity said calmly.

Dr. Charles struggled as an invisible force dragged him forward.

<span style="color:blue;">“No-no, please-”</span>

<span style="color:red;">“The labyrinth hunts you with fear,”</span> the creature continued.

<span style="color:red;">“But this room...”</span>

Dr. Charles was thrown inside.

<span style="color:red;">“...removes everything else.”</span>

He collapsed onto the cold floor.

The walls were featureless grey. Smooth. Endless. No seams. No openings.

The space was silent.

Utterly silent.

Dr. Charles scrambled to his feet and slammed his hands against the walls.

<span style="color:blue;">“LET ME OUT!”</span>

Nothing answered.

No footsteps.

No voice.

No sound except his own breathing.

Outside the room, the entity watched quietly as the invisible boundary sealed shut.

<span style="color:red;">“You ran from your fear,” it said softly.</span>

<span style="color:red;">“And now you will have eternity to sit with it.”</span>

Dr. Charles began screaming.

But inside the empty room, the screams had nowhere to go.

They simply echoed back to him.

Forever.

